# ripgrep configuration — loaded via $RIPGREP_CONFIG_PATH (set in .zshenv).
#
# CAUTION: $RIPGREP_CONFIG_PATH is read by EVERY rg invocation in the
# environment, not just the interactive prompt. That includes Neovim's
# `grepprg=rg --vimgrep` (configs/editor/nvim/vimrc) and vim-gitgutter's
# `g:gitgutter_grep = 'rg'`. So this file MUST NOT change which lines rg
# emits or how it formats them, or it would corrupt Vim's quickfix parsing
# and gitgutter's hunk detection. That deliberately rules out --max-columns,
# --hidden, --no-ignore, and friends. Only safe, additive defaults belong here.

# Case-insensitive when the pattern is all lowercase; case-sensitive when it
# contains an uppercase letter. For lowercase patterns this is a matching
# superset (never hides a match). Vim `:grep` inherits the same convenience;
# override a single search with `rg -s` / `:grep -s` if you need exact case.
--smart-case

# Belt-and-braces: never descend into .git metadata. rg already skips hidden
# paths by default, so this only takes effect if someone adds --hidden on the
# CLI — harmless otherwise.
--glob=!.git/*

# Cosmetic only. rg keeps --color=auto, so these definitions are emitted to a
# TTY and silently dropped when output is piped (Vim, scripts) — no change to
# output format for non-interactive consumers.
--colors=line:fg:yellow
--colors=match:fg:red
--colors=path:fg:green
